      <div class="container mx-auto px-4 max-w-4xl">
        <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-cyan-400 p-8 md:p-10">
          <h2 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-8 leading-[0.9]">FAQ FOR DROPSHIPPING SELLERS</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">Do I need expensive dropshipping apps?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, if you want to scale past 50 orders/day. Starter dropshippers can manually import products and forward orders for $0 extra. But once you hit 50+ orders/day, you're drowning in copy-paste. DSers ($29/month) automates AliExpress orders. Syncee ($49/month) connects to multiple suppliers. Inventory Source ($99/month) syncs stock in real-time. DropShipPro spent $400/month on apps and saved 5+ hours/day. That's $75/hour worth of time. The apps pay for themselves 10x over if you're actually selling. If you're doing less than 20 orders/month, skip the apps, do it manually, upgrade when you hit the ceiling.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">How many products should I launch with?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">50-100 quality products beats 500 generic ones. Most dropshippers import 1,000 products from AliExpress and wonder why nobody buys. Problem: generic descriptions, supplier photos, no optimization. Better strategy: launch with 50 products, each with custom descriptions, custom photos, keyword-optimized titles, clear shipping times. DropShipPro relaunched with 127 custom products (down from 847) and saw 4.1% conversion rate vs. 1.2% before. Quality over quantity. Once you have the system dialed in, scale to 500, then 1,000 products. But start with 50 killer products, not 500 mediocre ones.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">Should I hide shipping times?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">No. Hide them and you lose 53% of customers to complaints. Dropshipping newbies think "if I tell them 14-day shipping, nobody will buy." So they hide it. Customer orders, expects 2-day shipping, waits 10 days, emails "where's my order?", you explain, they're pissed, leave bad review, chargeback. DropShipPro used to hide shipping times: 47 complaints/month, 8.3% refund rate. They added "Ships in 7-14 days" everywhere: 8 complaints/month, 2.1% refund rate. Customers don't mind 14-day shipping IF you tell them upfront. They mind 14-day shipping when they expected 2-day shipping. Set expectations, keep customers.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">Which is better: AliExpress dropshipping or US suppliers?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">AliExpress for margins, US suppliers for speed. AliExpress = 7-14 day shipping, 50-70% margins, 500,000+ products. US suppliers = 2-5 day shipping, 20-40% margins, limited product selection. DropShipPro uses AliExpress for 90% of products (winning product testing, trend-based items) and US suppliers for 10% (premium items, repeat customers). Hybrid approach: test products on AliExpress ($15 cost, sell for $47 = 68% margin), once product proves itself, source US version ($28 cost, sell for $59 = 53% margin, faster shipping = fewer complaints, higher repeat purchase). Start with AliExpress, scale winners to US suppliers.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">When should I migrate from Wix to Shopify?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">When you hit 500 products or $20K/month revenue. Wix is great for starters: cheaper, easier, good for 50-100 products. But it hits ceilings: app ecosystem smaller, automation limited, template lock-in. Signs you've outgrown Wix: (1) spending 3+ hours/day on operations that should be automated, (2) can't integrate suppliers you need, (3) hitting product limits, (4) revenue plateaus at $15-20K/month. One dropshipper migrated at $18K/month on Wix, hit $51K/month in 90 days on Shopify (automation freed time for marketing). Migrate when the pain of staying outweighs the pain of switching.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-b border-gray-200 pb-6">
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">How much should I budget for my dropshipping store?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">$150-500/month for real dropshipping operation. Minimal viable setup: Shopify ($29/month) + DSers ($29/month) = $58/month. But that's bare bones. Real dropshipping stack: Shopify Basic ($29) + DSers ($29) + Syncee ($49) + Inventory Source ($99) + reviews app ($29) + email marketing ($29) = $264/month. DropShipPro spent $400/month on apps alone. If $400/month sounds expensive, you're not ready for dropshipping. This isn't "build a $50 website and hope." This is "build a $400/month system that prints money." If you're serious, budget $300-500/month. If that breaks the bank, start with Wix ($27/month) and upgrade when you're making $5K+.</p>
            </div>

            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900 text-xl mb-2">Can dropshipping still work in 2025 with saturation?</p>
              <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, but not with 2018 tactics. "Import 1,000 products, set and forget" = guaranteed failure in 2025. Winners in 2025: custom descriptions (not generic supplier copy), custom photography (not supplier photos everyone uses), clear shipping expectations (not hiding delivery times), mobile-first checkout (81% of orders), automation at scale (manual ops cap at 50 orders/day). DropShipPro did $51K/month in 2025 (post-2024 algorithm changes). Their secret wasn't better products. It was better execution. Same AliExpress products as everyone else. Different presentation, different automation, different results. Dropshipping works. Lazy dropshipping doesn't.</p>
            </div>
